# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mixed-signal-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In electronics, an **analog-to-digital converter** (**ADC**, **A/D**, or **A-to-D**) is a system that converts an analog signal, such as from fingers touching a touchscreen, sound entering a microphone, or light entering a digital camera, into a digital signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] An ADC may also provide an isolated measurement, such as an electronic device that converts an analog input voltage or current to a digital number representing the magnitude of the voltage or current.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Typically, the digital output is a two's complement binary number that is proportional to the input, but there are other possibilities.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Due to the complexity and the need for precisely matched components, all but the most specialized ADCs are implemented as integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] These typically take the form of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) mixed-signal integrated circuit chips that integrate both analog and digital circuits.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A digital-to-analog converter (DAC) performs the reverse function; it converts a digital signal into an analog signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] An ADC converts a continuous-time and continuous-amplitude analog signal to a discrete-time and discrete-amplitude digital signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The conversion involves quantization of the input, so it necessarily introduces a small amount of quantization error.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Furthermore, instead of continuously performing the conversion, an ADC does the conversion periodically, sampling the input, and limiting the allowable bandwidth of the input signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The performance of an ADC is primarily characterized by its bandwidth, dynamic range and signal-to-noise and distortion ratio (SNDR).
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The bandwidth of an ADC is set largely by its sampling rate.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The SNDR is influenced by many factors, including the resolution, noise floor, linearity and accuracy (how well the quantization levels match the true analog signal).
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Aliasing and jitter will degrade these specifications.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The SNDR of an ADC is often summarized in terms of its effective number of bits (ENOB), the number of bits of each measure it returns that are, on average, not noise.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] An ideal ADC has an ENOB equal to its resolution.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] If an ADC operates at a sampling rate greater than twice the bandwidth of the signal, then per the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, near-perfect reconstruction is possible.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The presence of quantization error limits the SNDR of even an ideal ADC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] When the SNDR of the ADC exceeds that of the input signal, the effects of quantization error may be neglected, resulting in an essentially perfect digital representation of the bandlimited analog input signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The resolution of the converter indicates the number of different, i.e., discrete, values it can produce over the allowed range of analog input values.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Thus, a particular resolution determines the magnitude of the quantization error and therefore determines the maximum possible signal-to-noise ratio for an ideal ADC without the use of oversampling.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The input samples are usually stored electronically in binary form within the ADC, so the resolution is usually expressed in bits.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Resolution can also be defined electrically, and expressed in volts.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The change in voltage required to guarantee a change in the output code level is called the least significant bit (LSB) voltage.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The resolution *Q* of the ADC is equal to the LSB voltage.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] where *M* is the ADC's resolution in bits and *E*FSR is the full-scale voltage range (also called 'span').
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] where *V*RefHi and *V*RefLow are the upper and lower extremes, respectively, of the voltages that can be coded.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] where *M* is the ADC's resolution in bits.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] That is, one voltage interval is assigned in between two consecutive code levels.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In many cases, the useful resolution of a converter is limited by the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) and other errors in the overall system expressed as an ENOB.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization error is introduced by the quantization inherent in an ideal ADC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] It is a rounding error between the analog input voltage to the ADC and the output digitized value.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The error is nonlinear and signal-dependent.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] where M is the number of quantization bits.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] For example, for a 16-bit ADC, the quantization error is 96.3 dB below the maximum level.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization error is distributed from DC to the Nyquist frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Consequently, if part of the ADC's bandwidth is not used, as is the case with oversampling, some of the quantization error will occur out-of-band, effectively improving the SQNR for the bandwidth in use.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In an oversampled system, noise shaping can be used to further increase SQNR by forcing more quantization error out of band.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In ADCs, performance can usually be improved using dither.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] This is a very small amount of random noise (e.g., white noise), which is added to the input before conversion.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Its effect is to randomize the state of the LSB based on the signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Rather than the signal simply getting cut off altogether at low levels, it extends the effective range of signals that the ADC can convert, at the expense of a slight increase in noise.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Dither can only increase the resolution of a sampler.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] It cannot improve the linearity, and thus, accuracy does not necessarily improve.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization distortion in an audio signal of very low level with respect to the bit depth of the ADC is correlated with the signal and sounds distorted and unpleasant.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] With dithering, the distortion is transformed into noise.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The undistorted signal may be recovered accurately by averaging over time.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Dithering is also used in integrating systems such as electricity meters.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Since the values are added together, the dithering produces results that are more exact than the LSB of the analog-to-digital converter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Dither is often applied when quantizing photographic images to a fewer number of bits per pixel—the image becomes noisier but to the eye looks far more realistic than the quantized image, which otherwise becomes banded.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] This analogous process may help to visualize the effect of dither on an analog audio signal that is converted to digital.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization error and (assuming the ADC is intended to be linear) non-linearity are intrinsic to any analog-to-digital conversion.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] These errors are measured in a unit called the least significant bit (LSB).
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In the above example of an 8-bit ADC, an error of one LSB is 1⁄256 of the full signal range, or about 0.4%.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] All ADCs suffer from nonlinearity errors caused by their physical imperfections, causing their output to deviate from a linear function (or some other function, in the case of a deliberately nonlinear ADC) of their input.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] These errors can sometimes be mitigated by calibration, or prevented by testing.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Important parameters for linearity are integral nonlinearity and differential nonlinearity.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] These nonlinearities introduce distortion that can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio performance of the ADC and thus reduce its effective resolution.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] When digitizing a sine wave $x(t)=A\sin {(2\pi f_{0}t)}$ , the use of a non-ideal sampling clock will result in some uncertainty in when samples are recorded.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Provided that the actual sampling time uncertainty due to clock jitter is $\Delta t$ , the error caused by this phenomenon can be estimated as $E_{ap}\leq |x'(t)\Delta t|\leq 2A\pi f_{0}\Delta t$ .
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] This will result in additional recorded noise that will reduce the effective number of bits (ENOB) below that predicted by quantization error alone.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The error is zero for DC, small at low frequencies, but significant with signals of high amplitude and high frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The effect of jitter on performance can be compared to quantization error: $\Delta t<{\frac {1}{2^{q}\pi f_{0}}}$ , where q is the number of ADC bits.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The resolution of ADCs with a digitization bandwidth between 1 MHz and 1 GHz is limited by jitter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] For lower bandwidth conversions such as when sampling audio signals at 44.1 kHz, clock jitter has a less significant impact on performance.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] An analog signal is continuous in time and it is necessary to convert this to a flow of digital values.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] It is therefore required to define the rate at which new digital values are sampled from the analog signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The rate of new values is called the *sampling rate* or *sampling frequency* of the converter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A continuously varying bandlimited signal can be sampled and then the original signal can be reproduced from the discrete-time values by a reconstruction filter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem implies that a faithful reproduction of the original signal is only possible if the sampling rate is higher than twice the highest frequency of the signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Since a practical ADC cannot make an instantaneous conversion, the input value must necessarily be held constant during the time that the converter performs a conversion (called the *conversion time*).
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] An input circuit called a sample and hold performs this task—in most cases by using a capacitor to store the analog voltage at the input, and using an electronic switch or gate to disconnect the capacitor from the input.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Many ADC integrated circuits include the sample and hold subsystem internally.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] An ADC works by sampling the value of the input at discrete intervals in time.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Provided that the input is sampled above the Nyquist rate, defined as twice the highest frequency of interest, then all frequencies in the signal can be reconstructed.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] If frequencies above half the Nyquist rate are sampled, they are incorrectly detected as lower frequencies, a process referred to as aliasing.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Aliasing occurs because instantaneously sampling a function at two or fewer times per cycle results in missed cycles, and therefore, the appearance of an incorrectly lower frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] For example, a 2 kHz sine wave being sampled at 1.5 kHz would be reconstructed as a 500 Hz sine wave.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] To avoid aliasing, the input to an ADC must be low-pass filtered to remove frequencies above half the sampling rate.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] This filter is called an *anti-aliasing filter*, and is essential for a practical ADC system that is applied to analog signals with higher frequency content.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In applications where protection against aliasing is essential, oversampling may be used to greatly reduce or even eliminate it.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Although aliasing in most systems is unwanted, it can be exploited to provide simultaneous down-mixing of a band-limited high-frequency signal (see undersampling and frequency mixer).
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The alias is effectively the lower heterodyne of the signal frequency and sampling frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] For economy, signals are often sampled at the minimum rate required, with the result that the quantization error introduced is white noise spread over the whole passband of the converter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Oversampling is typically used in audio frequency ADCs where the required sampling rate (typically 44.1 or 48 kHz) is very low compared to the clock speed of typical transistor circuits (>1 MHz).
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In this case, the performance of the ADC can be greatly increased at little or no cost.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Furthermore, as any aliased signals are also typically out of band, aliasing can often be eliminated using very low-cost filters.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The sliding scale method was introduced in 1963 by Cottini, Gatti, and Svelto as a way to reduce differential nonlinearity in analog-to-digital converters used in radiation detection systems.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In those applications, the digital output codes of an ADC are accumulated into histograms representing measured particle energies.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] If some output codes correspond to slightly wider or narrower input voltage ranges than others, the resulting *bins* in the histogram are uneven.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] This produces visible structure in what should otherwise be smooth spectra.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The method works by adding a known random analog offset to the input before conversion and subtracting the corresponding digital value afterward.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Although the final numerical result is unchanged, each conversion effectively occurs at a different position along the ADC transfer characteristic.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] When many samples are accumulated, the output codes represent an average over several adjacent code widths, reducing the impact of differential nonlinearity.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] There are several common ways of implementing an electronic ADC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Resistor-capacitor (RC) circuits have a known voltage charging and discharging curve that can be used to solve for an unknown analog value.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The Wilkinson ADC is a type of linear ramp converter, originally described by Denys Wilkinson in 1950.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In this architecture, the input pulse is compared with a linearly voltage ramp generated by charging a capacitor with a constant current source.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A comparator produces a gate signal that remains active until the ramp reaches the amplitude of the input pulse.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The duration of this gate interval is therefore proportional to the input amplitude.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] During this interval, pulses from a constant-frequency clock are counted by a register, and the final count represents the digital output.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Because the ramp can be generated with high precision, the output codes are contiguous and nearly uniform in width, giving the converter good differential linearity.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The conversion time is proportional to the input amplitude and inversely proportional to the clock frequency, so larger signals require longer conversion times.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Wilkinson converters were widely used in multichannel analyzers for nuclear spectroscopy through the 1960s and 1970s due to their linearity and suitability for histogram-based measurements.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] and solving for the unknown resistance or capacitance using those starting and ending datapoints.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] This is similar but contrasts with the Wilkinson ADC, which measures an unknown voltage with a known resistance and capacitance, by instead measuring an unknown resistance or capacitance with a known voltage.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] For example, the positive (and/or negative) pulse width from a 555 Timer IC in monostable or astable mode represents the time it takes to charge (and/or discharge) its capacitor from 1⁄3 *V*supply to 2⁄3 *V*supply.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] By sending this pulse into a microcontroller with an accurate clock, the duration of the pulse can be measured and converted using the capacitor charging equation to produce the value of the unknown resistance or capacitance.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Larger resistances and capacitances will take a longer time to measure than smaller ones.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] And the accuracy is limited by the accuracy of the microcontroller clock and the amount of time available to measure the value, which potentially might even change during measurement or be affected by external parasitics.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A flash ADC, also known as a parallel search ADC, employs a bank of voltage comparators sampling the input signal in parallel, each with a different voltage threshold.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The circuit consists of a resistive divider network, a set of voltage comparators and a priority encoder.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Each node of the resistive divider provides a voltage threshold for one comparator.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The comparator outputs are applied to a priority encoder, which generates a binary number proportional to the input voltage.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Flash ADCs have a large die size and high power dissipation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] They are used in a variety of applications, including video, wideband communications, and for digitizing other fast signals.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The circuit has the advantage of high speed as the conversion takes place simultaneously rather than sequentially.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Typical conversion time is 100 ns or less.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Conversion time is limited only by the speed of the comparator and of the priority encoder.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] This type of ADC has the disadvantage that for each additional output bit, the number of comparators required almost doubles, and the priority encoder becomes more complex.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A successive-approximation ADC uses a comparator and a binary search to successively narrow a range that contains the input voltage.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] At each successive step, the converter compares the input voltage to the output of an internal digital-to-analog converter (DAC), which initially represents the midpoint of the allowed input voltage range.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] At each step in this process, the approximation is stored in a successive approximation register (SAR) and the output of the digital-to-analog converter is updated for a comparison over a narrower range.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A ramp-compare ADC produces a saw-tooth signal that ramps up or down, then quickly returns to zero.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] When the ramp starts, a timer starts counting.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] When the ramp voltage matches the input, a comparator fires, and the timer's value is recorded.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Timed ramp converters can be implemented economically, however, the ramp time may be sensitive to temperature because the circuit generating the ramp is often a simple analog integrator.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A more accurate converter uses a clocked counter driving a DAC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A special advantage of the ramp-compare system is that converting a second signal just requires another comparator and another register to store the timer value.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] To reduce sensitivity to input changes during conversion, a sample and hold can charge a capacitor with the instantaneous input voltage and the converter can time the time required to discharge with a constant current.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] An **integrating ADC** (also **dual-slope** or **multi-slope** ADC) applies the unknown input voltage to the input of an integrator and allows the voltage to ramp for a fixed time period (the run-up period).
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Then a known reference voltage of opposite polarity is applied to the integrator and is allowed to ramp until the integrator output returns to zero (the run-down period).
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The input voltage is computed as a function of the reference voltage, the constant run-up time period, and the measured run-down time period.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The run-down time measurement is usually made in units of the converter's clock, so longer integration times allow for higher resolutions.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Likewise, the speed of the converter can be improved by sacrificing resolution.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Converters of this type (or variations on the concept) are used in most digital voltmeters for their linearity and flexibility.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] This frequency is then measured by a counter and converted to an output code proportional to the analog input.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The main advantage of these converters is that it is possible to transmit frequency even in a noisy environment or in isolated form.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] However, the limitation of this circuit is that the output of the voltage-to-frequency converter depends upon an RC product whose value cannot be accurately maintained over temperature and time.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The analog part of the circuit consists of a high input impedance buffer, precision integrator and a voltage comparator.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The converter first integrates the analog input signal for a fixed duration and then it integrates an internal reference voltage of opposite polarity until the integrator output is zero.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The main disadvantage of this circuit is the long duration time.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A *delta-encoded* or *counter-ramp* ADC has an up-down counter that feeds a DAC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The input signal and the DAC both go to a comparator.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The circuit uses negative feedback from the comparator to adjust the counter until the DAC's output matches the input signal and number is read from the counter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Delta converters have very wide ranges and high resolution, but the conversion time is dependent on the input signal behavior, though it will always have a guaranteed worst-case.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Delta converters are often very good choices to read real-world signals as most signals from physical systems do not change abruptly.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Some converters combine the delta and successive approximation approaches; this works especially well when high-frequency components of the input signal are known to be small in magnitude.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A *pipelined ADC* (also called *subranging quantizer*) uses two or more conversion steps.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In a second step, the difference to the input signal is determined with a DAC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] This difference is then converted more precisely, and the results are combined in the last step.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] This can be considered a refinement of the successive-approximation ADC wherein the feedback reference signal consists of the interim conversion of a whole range of bits (for example, four bits) rather than just the next-most-significant bit.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] By combining the merits of the successive approximation and flash ADCs this type is fast, has a high resolution, and can be implemented efficiently.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A **delta-sigma ADC** (also known as a **sigma-delta ADC**) is based on a negative feedback loop with an analog filter and low resolution (often 1 bit) but high sampling rate ADC and DAC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The feedback loop continuously corrects accumulated quantization errors and performs noise shaping: quantization noise is reduced in the low frequencies of interest, but is increased in higher frequencies.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Those higher frequencies may then be removed by a downsampling digital filter, which also converts the data stream from that high sampling rate with low bit depth to a lower rate with higher bit depth.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A time-interleaved ADC uses M parallel ADCs where each ADC samples data every M:th cycle of the effective sample clock.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The result is that the sample rate is increased M times compared to what each individual ADC can manage.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In practice, the individual differences between the M ADCs degrade the overall performance reducing the spurious-free dynamic range (SFDR).
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] However, techniques exist to correct for these time-interleaving mismatch errors.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Longer integration times allow for higher resolutions.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The two parts of the ADC may be widely separated, with the frequency signal passed through an opto-isolator or transmitted wirelessly.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Some such ADCs use sine wave or square wave frequency modulation; others use pulse-frequency modulation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Such ADCs were once the most popular way to show a digital display of the status of a remote analog sensor.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] A time-stretch analog-to-digital converter (TS-ADC) digitizes a very wide bandwidth analog signal, that cannot be digitized by a conventional electronic ADC, by time-stretching the signal prior to digitization.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] It commonly uses a photonic preprocessor to time-stretch the signal, which effectively slows the signal down in time and compresses its bandwidth.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] As a result, an electronic ADC, that would have been too slow to capture the original signal, can now capture this slowed-down signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] For continuous capture of the signal, the front end also divides the signal into multiple segments in addition to time-stretching.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Each segment is individually digitized by a separate electronic ADC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Finally, a digital signal processor rearranges the samples and removes any distortions added by the preprocessor to yield the binary data that is the digital representation of the original analog signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] In many cases, the most expensive part of an integrated circuit is the pins, because they make the package larger, and each pin has to be connected to the integrated circuit's silicon.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] To save pins, it is common for ADCs to send their data one bit at a time over a serial interface to the computer, with each bit coming out when a clock signal changes state.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] This saves quite a few pins on the ADC package, and in many cases, does not make the overall design any more complex.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Commercial ADCs often have several inputs that feed the same converter, usually through an analog multiplexer.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Different models of ADC may include sample and hold circuits, instrumentation amplifiers or differential inputs, where the quantity measured is the difference between two inputs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Soundstream was probably the first digital audio recording system of commercial importance.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Analog-to-digital converters are integral to modern music reproduction technology and digital audio workstation-based sound recording.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Music may be produced on computers using an analog recording and therefore analog-to-digital converters are needed to create the pulse-code modulation (PCM) data streams that go onto compact discs and digital music files.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] The current crop of analog-to-digital converters utilized in music can sample at rates up to 192 kilohertz.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Many recording studios record in 24-bit 96 kHz pulse-code modulation (PCM) format and then downsample and dither the signal for Compact Disc Digital Audio production (44.1 kHz) or to 48 kHz for radio and television broadcast applications.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] ADCs are required in digital signal processing systems that process, store, or transport virtually any analog signal in digital form.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] TV tuner cards, for example, use fast video analog-to-digital converters.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Slow on-chip 8-, 10-, 12-, or 16-bit analog-to-digital converters are common in microcontrollers.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Digital storage oscilloscopes need very fast analog-to-digital converters, also crucial for software-defined radio and their new applications.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Digital imaging systems commonly use analog-to-digital converters for digitizing pixels.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Some radar systems use analog-to-digital converters to convert signal strength to digital values for subsequent signal processing.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Many other in situ and remote sensing systems commonly use analogous technology.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Many sensors in scientific instruments produce an analog signal; temperature, pressure, pH, light intensity etc.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] All these signals can be amplified and fed to an ADC to produce a digital representation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Flat-panel displays are inherently digital and need an ADC to process an analog signal such as composite or VGA.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Testing an analog-to-digital converter requires an analog input source and hardware to send control signals and capture digital data output.
[src:mixed-signal-design/analog-to-digital-converter] Some ADCs also require an accurate source of reference signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Both ADCs and DACs can employ delta-sigma modulation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] A delta-sigma ADC (e.g., Figure 1 top) encodes an analog signal using high-frequency delta-sigma modulation and then applies a digital filter to demodulate it to a high-bit digital output at a lower sampling frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] A delta-sigma DAC (e.g., Figure 1 bottom) encodes a high-resolution digital input signal into a lower-resolution, but higher sample-frequency signal that may then be mapped to voltages and smoothed with an analog filter for demodulation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] In both cases, the temporary use of a low bit depth signal at a higher sampling frequency simplifies circuit design and takes advantage of the efficiency and high accuracy in time of digital electronics.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Primarily because of its cost efficiency and reduced circuit complexity, this technique has found increasing use in modern electronic components such as DACs, ADCs, frequency synthesizers, switched-mode power supplies and motor controllers.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The coarsely-quantized output of a delta-sigma ADC is occasionally used directly in signal processing or as a representation for signal storage (e.g., Super Audio CD stores the raw output of a 1-bit delta-sigma modulator).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] While this article focuses on synchronous modulation, which requires a precise clock for quantization, asynchronous delta-sigma modulation instead runs without a clock.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] When transmitting an analog signal directly, all noise in the system and transmission is added to the analog signal, reducing its quality.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Digitizing it enables noise-free transmission, storage, and processing.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] In Nyquist-rate ADCs, an analog signal is sampled at a relatively low sampling frequency just above its Nyquist rate (twice the signal's highest frequency) and quantized by a multi-level quantizer to produce a multi-bit digital signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Such higher-bit methods seek accuracy in amplitude directly, but require extremely precise components and so may suffer from poor linearity.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Oversampling converters instead produce a lower bit depth result at a much higher sampling frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Another key aspect given by oversampling is the frequency/resolution tradeoff.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The decimation filter put after the modulator not only filters the whole sampled signal in the band of interest (cutting the noise at higher frequencies), but also reduces the sampling rate, and hence the representable frequency range, of the signal, while increasing the sample amplitude resolution.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This improvement in amplitude resolution is obtained by a sort of *averaging* of the higher-data-rate bitstream.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Delta modulation is an earlier related low-bit oversampling method that also uses negative feedback, but only encodes the derivative of the signal (its *delta*) rather than its amplitude.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The result is a stream of marks and spaces representing up or down movement of the signal, which must be integrated to reconstruct the signal's amplitude.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The differentiation alters the signal's spectrum by amplifying high-frequency noise, attenuating low-frequencies, and dropping the DC component.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This makes its dynamic range and signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) inversely proportional to signal frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Delta modulation suffers from slope overload if signals move too fast.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] And it is susceptible to transmission disturbances that result in cumulative error.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Delta-sigma modulation rearranges the integrator and quantizer of a delta modulator so that the output carries information corresponding to the amplitude of the input signal instead of just its derivative.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This also has the benefit of incorporating desirable noise shaping into the conversion process, to deliberately move quantization noise to frequencies higher than the signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] In the specific case of a single-bit synchronous ΔΣ ADC, an analog voltage signal is effectively converted into a pulse frequency, or pulse density, which can be understood as pulse-density modulation (PDM).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] A sequence of positive and negative pulses, representing bits at a known fixed rate, is very easy to generate, transmit, and accurately regenerate at the receiver, given only that the timing and sign of the pulses can be recovered.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Given such a sequence of pulses from a delta-sigma modulator, the original waveform can be reconstructed with adequate precision.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The use of PDM as a signal representation is an alternative to PCM.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Alternatively, the high-frequency PDM can later be downsampled through decimation and requantized to convert it into a multi-bit PCM code at a lower sampling frequency closer to the Nyquist rate of the frequency band of interest.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The seminal paper combining feedback with oversampling to achieve delta modulation was by F. de Jager of Philips Research Laboratories in 1952.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The principle of improving the resolution of a coarse quantizer by use of feedback, which is the basic principle of delta-sigma conversion, was first described in a 1954-filed patent by C.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] It was not named as such until a 1962 paper by Inose et al. of University of Tokyo, which came up with the idea of adding a filter in the forward path of the delta modulator.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] However, Charles B Brahm of United Aircraft Corp in 1961 filed a patent "Feedback integrating system" with a feedback loop containing an integrator with multi-bit quantization shown in its Fig 1.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Wooley's "The Evolution of Oversampling Analog-to-Digital Converters" gives more history and references to relevant patents.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Some avenues of variation (which may be applied in different combinations) are the modulator's order, the quantizer's bit depth, the manner of decimation, and the oversampling ratio.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Noise of the quantizer can be further shaped by replacing the quantizer itself with another ΔΣ modulator.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This creates a second-order modulator, which can be rearranged in a cascaded fashion (Figure 2).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This process can be repeated to increase the order even more.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] While first-order modulators are unconditionally stable, stability analysis must be performed for higher-order noise-feedback modulators.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The modulator can also be classified by the bit depth of its quantizer.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] A quantizer that distinguishes between *N-levels* is called a *log2N* bit quantizer.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] For example, a simple comparator has 2 levels and so is a 1-bit quantizer; a 3-level quantizer is called a *1.5* bit quantizer; a 4-level quantizer is a 2-bit quantizer; a 5-level quantizer is called a *2.5-bit* quantizer.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Higher bit quantizers inherently produce less quantization noise.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] One criticism of 1-bit quantization is that adequate amounts of dither cannot be used in the feedback loop, so distortion can be heard under some conditions (more discussion at Direct Stream Digital § DSD vs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Many of the issues of 1-bit modulation can be treated by look-ahead sigma-delta modulation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Decimation is strongly associated with delta-sigma modulation, but is distinct and outside the scope of this article.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The original 1962 paper didn't describe decimation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Oversampled data in the early days was sent as is.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The proposal to decimate oversampled delta-sigma data using digital filtering before converting it into PCM audio was made by D.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Goodman at Bell Labs in 1969, to reduce the ΔΣ signal from its high sampling rate while increasing its bit depth.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Decimation may be done in a separate chip on the receiving end of the delta-sigma bit stream, sometimes by a dedicated module inside of a microcontroller, which is useful for interfacing with PDM MEMS microphones, though many ΔΣ ADC integrated circuits include decimation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Some microcontrollers even incorporate both the modulator and decimator.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Cascaded integrator–comb filters: These are called sincN filters, equivalent to cascading the above sinc1 filter N times and rearranging the order of operations for computational efficiency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Lower N filters are simpler, settle faster, and have less attenuation in the baseband, while higher N filters are slightly more complex and settle slower and have more droop in the passband, but better attenuate undesired high-frequency noise.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Compensation filters can, however, be applied to counteract undesired passband attenuation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] SincN filters are appropriate for decimating sigma delta modulation down to four times the Nyquist rate.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Windowed sinc-in-time (brick-wall in frequency) filters: Although the sinc function's infinite support prevents it from being realizable in finite time, the sinc function can instead be windowed to realize finite impulse response filters.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This approximated filter design, while maintaining *almost no* attenuation of the lower-frequency band of interest, still removes *almost all* undesired high-frequency noise.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The downside is poor performance in the time domain (e.g. step response overshoot and ripple), higher delay (i.e. their convolution time is inversely proportional to their cutoff transition steepness), and higher computational requirements.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] They are the de facto standard for high fidelity digital audio converters.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Most commercial ΔΣ modulators use integrators as the loop filter, because, as low-pass filters, they push quantization noise up in frequency, which is useful for baseband signals.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] But a ΔΣ modulator's filter does not necessarily need to be a low-pass filter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] If a band-pass filter is used instead, then quantization noise is moved up and down in frequency away from the filter's pass-band, so a subsequent pass-band decimation filter will result in a ΔΣ ADC with a bandpass characteristic.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] When a signal is quantized, the resulting signal can be approximated by the addition of white noise with approximately equal intensity across the entire spectrum.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] In reality, the quantization noise is, of course, not independent of the signal and this dependence results in limit cycles and is the source of idle tones and pattern noise in delta-sigma converters.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] However, adding dithering noise (Figure 3) reduces such distortion by making quantization noise more random.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] ΔΣ ADCs reduce the amount of this noise in the baseband by spreading it out and shaping it so it is mostly in higher frequencies.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] It can then be easily filtered out with inexpensive digital filters, without high-precision analog circuits needed by Nyquist ADCs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] where $f_{\mathrm {s} }$ is the sampling frequency and $2f_{0}$ is the Nyquist rate (the minimum sampling rate needed to avoid aliasing, which is twice the original signal's maximum frequency $f_{0}$ ).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Since oversampling is typically done in powers of two, d represents how many times OSR is doubled.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] As illustrated in Figure 4, the total amount of quantization noise is the same both in a Nyquist converter (yellow + green areas) and in an oversampling converter (blue + green areas).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] But oversampling converters distribute that noise over a much wider frequency range.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The benefit is that the total amount of noise in the frequency band of interest is dramatically smaller for oversampling converters (just the small green area), than for a Nyquist converter (yellow + green total area).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Figure 4 shows how ΔΣ modulation shapes noise to further reduce the amount of quantization noise in the baseband in exchange for increasing noise at higher frequencies (where it can be easily filtered out).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The curves of higher-order ΔΣ modulators achieve even greater reduction of noise in the baseband.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] These curves are derived using mathematical tools called the Laplace transform (for continuous-time signals, e.g., in an ADC's modulation loop) or the Z-transform (for discrete-time signals, e.g. in a DAC's modulation loop).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] These transforms are useful for converting harder math from the time domain into simpler math in the complex frequency domain of the complex variable ${\text{s}}=\sigma +j\omega$ (in the Laplace domain) or ${\text{z}}=Ae^{j\phi }$ (in the z-domain).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The Laplace transform of integration of a function of time corresponds to simply multiplication by ${\tfrac {1}{\text{s}}}$ in Laplace notation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The integrator is assumed to be an ideal integrator to keep the math simple, but a real integrator (or similar filter) may have a more complicated expression.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The process of quantization is approximated as addition with a quantization error noise source.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The noise is often assumed to be white and independent of the signal, though as quantization (signal processing) § Additive noise model explains, that is not always a valid assumption (particularly for low-bit quantization).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This transfer function has a single pole at ${\text{s}}={\text{-1}}$ in the complex plane, so it effectively acts as a first-order low-pass filter on the input signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] (Note: its cutoff frequency could be adjusted as desired by including multiplication by a constant in the loop).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This transfer function has a single zero at ${\text{s}}=0$ and a single pole at ${\text{s}}={\text{-1}},$ so the system effectively acts as a high-pass filter on the noise that starts at 0 at DC, then gradually rises until it reaches the cutoff frequency, and then levels off.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The synchronous ΔΣ DAC's modulation loop (Figure 6), meanwhile, is in discrete-time and so its analysis is in the z-domain.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] It is very similar to the above analysis in the Laplace domain and produces similar curves.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Note: many sources§6.1 also analyzes a ΔΣ ADC's modulation loop in the z-domain, which implicitly treats the continuous analog input as a discrete-time signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This may be a valid approximation provided that the input signal is already bandlimited and can be assumed to be not changing on time scales higher than the sampling rate.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] It is particularly appropriate when the modulator is implemented as a switched capacitor circuit, which works by transferring charge between capacitors in clocked time steps.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Its transfer function ${\tfrac {1}{1-{\text{z}}^{\text{-1}}}}$ is often used to label integrators in block diagrams.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] In a ΔΣ DAC, the quantizer may be called a *requantizer* or a *digital-to-digital converter* (DDC), because its input is already digital and quantized but is simply reducing from a higher bit depth to a lower bit depth digital signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This is represented in the z-domain by another ${\text{z}}^{\text{-1}}$ delay stage in series with adding quantization noise.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The noise term's multiplication by $(1-{\text{z}}^{\text{-1}})$ represents a *first difference backward* filter (which has a single pole at the origin and a single zero at ${\text{z}}{=}1$ ) and thus high-pass filters the noise.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] For comparison, oversampling a Nyquist ADC (without any noise shaping) only improves its ENOB by ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ bits for every doubling of the OSR, which is only 1⁄3 of the ENOB growth rate of a first-order ΔΣM.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] In practice, circuits inevitably experience other noise sources that limit resolution, making the higher-resolution cells impractical.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Assuming quantization were homogeneous (e.g., if it were linear), that integrator can be moved from the demodulator to instead be on the input signal, before the summation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The linearity property of integration, ${\textstyle \int a+\int b=\int (a+b),}$ allows the two integrators to be combined, so a delta-sigma modulator and demodulator is obtained.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] But because the quantizer is *not* homogeneous, the above is not a sufficient derivation of their hypothetical equivalence, so while delta-sigma is *inspired* by delta modulation, the two are distinct in operation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] From the first block diagram in Figure 7, the integrator in the feedback path can be removed if the feedback is taken directly from the input of the low-pass filter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] In other words, doing delta-sigma modulation instead of delta modulation has effectively swapped the ordering of the integrator and quantizer operations.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The net effect is a simpler implementation that has the profound added benefit of shaping the quantization noise to be mostly in frequencies above the signals of interest.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This effect becomes more dramatic with increased oversampling, which allows for quantization noise to be somewhat programmable.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] On the other hand, delta modulation shapes both noise and signal equally.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Additionally, the quantizer (e.g., comparator) used in delta modulation has a small output representing a small step up and down the quantized approximation of the input while the quantizer used in delta-sigma must take values *outside* of the range of the input signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Figure 8a: Schematic of a simple delta-sigma converter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Figure 8b: Simulated scope view of key voltage signals over time.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Each minor vertical division is 1 μs, which corresponds to a sampling event of the 1 MHz clock.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The circuit below focuses on a simple first-order, two-level quantization synchronous delta-sigma ADC without decimation.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] To ease understanding, a simple circuit schematic (Figure 8a) using ideal elements is simulated (Figure 8b voltages).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The 20 kHz input sine wave **s(t)** is converted to a 1-bit PDM digital result **Q(t)**.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] 20 kHz is used as an example because that is considered the upper limit of human hearing.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This circuit can be laid out on a breadboard with inexpensive discrete components (note some variations use different biasing and use simpler RC low-pass filters for integration instead of op amps).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] For simplicity, the D flip-flop is powered by dual supply voltages of VDD = +1 V and VSS = -1 V, so its binary output **Q(t)** is either +1 V or -1 V.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The 2-input inverting op amp integrator combines **s(t)** with **Q(t)** to produce **Ɛ(t)**: $\varepsilon (t)=-{\frac {1}{RC}}\int (s(t)+Q(t))dt.$ The Greek letter epsilon is used because **Ɛ(t)** contains the accumulated error that is repeatedly corrected by the feedback mechanism.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] While both its inputs **s(t)** and **Q(t)** vary between -1 and 1 volts, **Ɛ(t)** instead only varies by a couple *millivolts* about 0 V.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Because of the integrator's *negative* sign, when **Ɛ(t)** next gets sampled to produce **Q(t)**, the +**Q(t)** in this integral actually represents *negative* feedback from the previous clock cycle.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] An ideal D flip-flop samples **Ɛ(t)** at the clock rate of 1 MHz.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The scope view (Figure 8b) has a minor division equal to the sampling period of 1 μs, so every minor division corresponds to a sampling event.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Since the flip-flop is assumed to be ideal, it treats any input voltage greater than 0 V as logical high and any input voltage smaller than 0 V as logical low, no matter how close it is to 0 V (ignoring issues of sample-and-hold time violations and metastability).
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The rightmost integrator performs digital-to-analog conversion on **Q(t)** to produce a demodulated analog output **r(t)**, which reconstructs the original sine wave input as piece-wise linear diagonal segments.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Although **r(t)** appears coarse at this 50x oversampling rate, **r(t)** can be low-pass filtered to isolate the original signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] As the sampling rate is increased relative to the input signal's maximum frequency, **r(t)** will more closely approximate the original input **s(t)**.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] It is worth noting that if no decimation ever took place, the digital representation from a 1-bit delta-sigma modulator is simply a PDM signal, which can easily be converted to analog using a low-pass filter, as simple as a resistor and capacitor.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] However, in general, a delta-sigma DAC converts a discrete time series signal of digital samples at a high bit depth into a low-bit-depth (often 1-bit) signal, usually at a much higher sampling rate.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] As the discrete Fourier transform and discrete-time Fourier transform articles explain, a periodically sampled signal inherently contains multiple higher frequency copies or *images* of the signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] It is often desirable to remove these higher-frequency images prior to performing the actual delta-sigma modulation stage, in order to ease requirements on the eventual analog low-pass filter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This can be done by upsampling using an interpolation filter and is often the first step prior to performing delta-sigma modulation in DACs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] This simple first-order modulation can be improved by cascading two or more overflowing accumulators, each of which is equivalent to a first-order delta-sigma modulator.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The resulting multi-stage noise shaping (MASH) structure has a steeper noise shaping property, so is commonly used in digital audio.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The carry outputs are combined through summations and delays to produce a binary output, the width of which depends on the number of stages (order) of the MASH.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The technique was first presented in the early 1960s by professor Yasuhiko Yasuda while he was a student at the University of Tokyo.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] The name *delta-sigma* comes directly from the presence of a delta modulator and an integrator, as firstly introduced by Inose et al. in their patent application.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] That is, the name comes from integrating or *summing* **differences**, which, in mathematics, are operations usually associated with Greek letters sigma and delta respectively.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Both names *sigma-delta* and *delta-sigma* are frequently used.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Kikkert and Miller published a continuous-time variant called Asynchronous Delta Sigma Modulation (ADSM or ASDM) in 1975, which uses either a Schmitt trigger (i.e. a comparator with hysteresis) or (as the paper argues is equivalent) a comparator with fixed delay.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] In the example in Figure 9, when the integral of the error exceeds its limits, the output changes state, producing a pulse-width modulated (PWM) output wave.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] Amplitude information is converted, without quantization noise, into time information of the output PWM.
[src:mixed-signal-design/delta-sigma-modulation] To convert this continuous time PWM to discrete time, the PWM may be sampled by a time-to-digital converter, whose limited resolution adds noise which can be shaped by feeding it back.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] In electronics, a **digital-to-analog converter** (**DAC**, **D/A**, **D2A**, or **D-to-A**) is a system that converts a digital signal into an analog signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] An analog-to-digital converter (ADC) performs the reverse function.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] DACs are commonly used in music players to convert digital data streams into analog audio signals.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] They are also used in televisions and mobile phones to convert digital video data into analog video signals.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] These two applications use DACs at opposite ends of the frequency/resolution trade-off.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The audio DAC is a low-frequency, high-resolution type, while the video DAC is a high-frequency low- to medium-resolution type.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] There are several DAC architectures; the suitability of a DAC for a particular application is determined by figures of merit, including: resolution, maximum sampling frequency and others.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Digital-to-analog conversion can degrade a signal, so a DAC should be specified that has insignificant errors in terms of the application.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Due to the complexity and the need for precisely matched components, all but the most specialized DACs are implemented as integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Discrete DACs (circuits constructed from multiple discrete electronic components instead of a packaged IC) would typically be extremely high-speed, low-resolution, power-hungry types, as used in military radar systems.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Very high-speed test equipment, especially sampling oscilloscopes, may also use discrete DACs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] A DAC converts an abstract finite-precision number (usually a fixed-point binary number) into a physical quantity (e.g., a voltage or a pressure).
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] In particular, DACs are often used to convert finite-precision time series data to a continually varying physical signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Provided that a signal's bandwidth meets the requirements of the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem (i.e., a baseband signal with bandwidth less than the Nyquist frequency) and was sampled with infinite resolution, the original signal can theoretically be reconstructed from the sampled data.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] However, an ADC's filtering can't *entirely* eliminate all frequencies above the Nyquist frequency, which will alias into the baseband frequency range.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] And the ADC's digital sampling process introduces some quantization error (rounding error), which manifests as low-level noise.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] These errors can be kept within the requirements of the targeted application (e.g. under the limited dynamic range of human hearing for audio applications).
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] In a typical telephone call, a microphone converts speech into an analog electrical signal, which is digitized by an ADC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The resulting digital data can be multiplexed with other digital information for transmission over a shared communication system.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] At the receiving end, a DAC converts the digital signal back into analog form so it can be amplified and reproduced as sound.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Early CD players used oversampling ahead of the D/A converter so that the analog reconstruction filter could be of low order and have a well-controlled phase response.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] In 1982, Philips described such a system in detail.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] A 16-bit, 44.1 kHz input is first applied to a digital interpolation filter and oversampled by a factor of four to 176.4 kHz.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The interpolation filter is a 96-tap finite impulse response network.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Its passband extends over the audio range, while the stopband attenuates the image components that would otherwise appear between 22 kHz and 88 kHz after zero-order hold conversion.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The higher sampling rate shifts these images away from the audio band and reduces the requirements on the analog filter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The filtered sequence is then represented with 14-bit precision and applied to the Philips TDA1540.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] This converter employs segmented current sources.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The larger current elements are subdivided and switched in a manner that averages element errors over time, an early form of dynamic element matching.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The result is improved linearity compared with a straightforward binary-weighted current source.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] At the output of the converter, the waveform consists of a staircase approximation to the desired signal, together with residual high-frequency components from the sampling process.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] A third-order analog low-pass filter follows the converter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] This filter removes the remaining out-of-band energy and provides the final smoothing of the waveform.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] A later device, the Philips TDA1541, provides full 16-bit resolution and removes the need for the intermediate word-length reduction step.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] In this and later designs, the same general arrangement was retained.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] This arrangement, digital interpolation followed by conversion and a relatively simple analog filter, became standard practice in CD playback and appears in later DACs such as the Crystal CS4397.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Most modern audio signals are stored in digital form (for example, MP3s and CDs), and in order to be heard through speakers, they must be converted into an analog signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] DACs are therefore found in CD players, digital music players, and PC sound cards.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Specialist standalone DACs can also be found in high-end hi-fi systems.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] These normally take the digital output of a compatible CD player or dedicated transport (which is basically a CD player with no internal DAC) and convert the signal into an analog line-level output that can then be fed into an amplifier to drive speakers.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Similar digital-to-analog converters can be found in digital speakers, such as USB speakers and in sound cards.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] In voice over IP applications, the source must first be digitized for transmission, so it undergoes conversion via an ADC and is then reconstructed into analog using a DAC on the receiving party's end.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Video signals from a digital source, such as a computer, must be converted to analog form if they are to be displayed on an analog monitor.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] As of 2007, analog inputs were more commonly used than digital, but this changed as flat-panel displays with DVI and/or HDMI connections became more widespread.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] A video DAC is, however, incorporated in any digital video player with analog outputs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The DAC is usually integrated with some memory (RAM), which contains conversion tables for gamma correction, contrast and brightness, to make a device called a RAMDAC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] A device that is distantly related to the DAC is the digitally controlled potentiometer, used to control an analog signal digitally.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] A one-bit mechanical actuator assumes two positions: one when on, another when off.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The motion of several one-bit actuators can be combined and weighted with a whiffletree mechanism to produce finer steps.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The IBM Selectric typewriter uses such a system.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] DACs are widely used in modern communication systems, enabling the generation of digitally defined transmission signals.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] High-speed DACs are used for mobile communications and ultra-high-speed DACs are employed in optical communications systems.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The number of possible output levels the DAC is designed to reproduce.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] , which is a measurement of the actual resolution attained by the DAC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] The maximum speed at which the DACs circuitry can operate and still produce correct output.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] A measurement of the distortion and noise introduced to the signal by the DAC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] and noise that accompanies the desired signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Other measurements, such as phase distortion and jitter, can also be very important for some applications, some of which (e.g., wireless data transmission, composite video) may even *rely* on accurate production of phase-adjusted signals.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] Non-linear PCM encodings (A-law / μ-law, ADPCM, NICAM) attempt to improve their effective dynamic ranges by using logarithmic step sizes between the output signal strengths represented by each data bit.
[src:mixed-signal-design/digital-to-analog-converter] This trades greater quantization distortion of loud signals for better performance of quiet signals.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] A **mixed-signal integrated circuit** is any integrated circuit that has both analog circuits and digital circuits on a single semiconductor die.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Their usage has grown dramatically with the increased use of cell phones, telecommunications, portable electronics, and automobiles with electronics and digital sensors.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Integrated circuits (ICs) are generally classified as digital (e.g. a microprocessor) or analog (e.g. an operational amplifier).
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Mixed-signal ICs contain both digital and analog circuitry on the same chip, and sometimes embedded software.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Mixed-signal ICs process both analog and digital signals together.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] For example, an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) is a typical mixed-signal circuit.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Mixed-signal ICs are often used to convert analog signals to digital signals so that digital devices can process them.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] For example, mixed-signal ICs are essential components for FM tuners in digital products such as media players, which have digital amplifiers.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Any analog signal can be digitized using a very basic ADC, and the smallest and most energy efficient of these are mixed-signal ICs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Mixed-signal ICs are more difficult to design and manufacture than analog-only or digital-only integrated circuits.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] For example, an efficient mixed-signal IC may have its digital and analog components share a common power supply.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] However, analog and digital components have very different power needs and consumption characteristics, which makes this a non-trivial goal in chip design.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Mixed-signal functionality involves both traditional active elements (like transistors) and well-performing passive elements (like coils, capacitors, and resistors) on the same chip.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] This requires additional modelling understanding and options from manufacturing technologies.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] High voltage transistors might be needed in the power management functions on a chip with digital functionality, possibly with a low-power CMOS processor system.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Some advanced mixed-signal technologies may enable combining analog sensor elements (like pressure sensors or imaging diodes) on the same chip with an ADC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Typically, mixed-signal ICs do not necessarily need the fastest digital performance.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Instead, they need more mature models of active and passive elements for more accurate simulations and verification, such as for testability planning and reliability estimations.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Therefore, mixed-signal circuits are typically realized with larger line widths than the highest speed and densest digital logic, and the implementation technologies can be two to four generations behind the latest digital-only implementation technologies.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Additionally, mixed signal processing may need passive elements like resistors, capacitors, and coils, which may require specialized metal, dielectric layers, or similar adaptations of standard fabrication processes.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Because of these specific requirements, mixed-signal ICs and digital ICs can have different manufacturers (known as foundries).
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Mixed-signal circuits or systems are typically cost-effective solutions, such as for building modern consumer electronics and in industrial, medical, measurement, and space applications.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Examples of mixed-signal integrated circuits include data converters using delta-sigma modulation, analog-to-digital converters and digital-to-analog converters using error detection and correction, and digital radio chips.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Digitally controlled sound chips are also mixed-signal circuits.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] With the advent of cellular and network technology, this category now includes cellular telephone, software radio, and LAN and WAN router integrated circuits.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Typically, mixed-signal chips perform some whole function or sub-function in a larger assembly, such as the radio subsystem of a cell phone, or the read data path and laser SLED control logic of a DVD player.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Mixed-signal ICs often contain an entire system-on-a-chip.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] They may also contain on-chip memory blocks (like OTP), which complicates the manufacturing compared to analog ICs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] A mixed-signal IC minimizes off-chip interconnects between digital and analog functionality in the system—typically reducing size and weight due to minimized packaging and a smaller module substrate—and therefore increases the reliability of the system.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Because of the use of both digital signal processing and analog circuitry, mixed-signal ICs are usually designed for a very specific purpose.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Their design requires a high level of expertise and careful use of computer aided design (CAD) tools.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] There also exists specific design tools (like mixed-signal simulators) or description languages (like VHDL-AMS).
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Automated testing of the finished chips can also be challenging.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Teradyne, Keysight, and Advantest are the major suppliers of the test equipment for mixed-signal chips.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Mixed-signal devices are available as standard parts, but sometimes custom-designed application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) are necessary.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] ASICs are designed for new applications, when new standards emerge, or when new energy source(s) are implemented in the system.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Due to their specialization, ASICs are usually only developed when production volumes are estimated to be high.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] The availability of ready-and-tested analog- and mixed-signal IP blocks from foundries or dedicated design houses has lowered the gap to realize mixed-signal ASICs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] There also exist mixed-signal field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) and microcontrollers.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] In these, the same chip that handles digital logic may contain mixed-signal structures like analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog converter(s), operational amplifiers, or wireless connectivity blocks.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] These mixed-signal FPGAs and microcontrollers are bridging the gap between standard mixed-signal devices, full-custom ASICs, and embedded software; they offer a solution during product development or when product volume is too low to justify an ASIC.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] However, they can have performance limitations, such as the resolution of the analog-to-digital converters, the speed of digital-to-analog conversion, or a limited number of inputs and outputs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Nevertheless, they can speed up the system architecture design, prototyping, and even production (at small and medium scales).
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Their usage also can be supported with development boards, development community, and possibly software support.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] The MOSFET was invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, after Frosch and Derick discovered and used surface passivation by silicon dioxide to create the first planar transistors, the first in which drain and source were adjacent at the same surface.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Robert Noyce and Jack Kilby invention of the silicon integrated circuit was enabled by the planar process developed by Jean Hoerni.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] In turn, Hoerni's planar process was inspired by the surface passivation method developed at Bell Labs by Carl Frosch and Lincoln Derick in 1955 and 1957.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] MOS technology eventually became practical for telephony applications with the MOS mixed-signal integrated circuit, which combines analog and digital signal processing on a single chip, developed by former Bell engineer David A.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] In 1974, Hodges and Gray worked with R.E.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Suarez to develop MOS switched capacitor (SC) circuit technology, which they used to develop a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) chip, using MOS capacitors and MOSFET switches for data conversion.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] MOS analog-to-digital converter (ADC) and DAC chips were commercialized by 1974.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] MOS SC circuits led to the development of pulse-code modulation (PCM) codec-filter chips in the late 1970s.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] The silicon-gate CMOS (complementary MOS) PCM codec-filter chip, developed by Hodges and W.C.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Black in 1980, has since been the industry standard for digital telephony.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] The bandwidth of digital telecommunication networks has been rapidly increasing at an exponential rate, as observed by Edholm's law, largely driven by the rapid scaling and miniaturization of MOS technology.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] While working at Bell Labs in the early 1980s, Pakistani engineer Asad Abidi worked on the development of sub-micron MOSFET (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor) VLSI (very large-scale integration) technology at the Advanced LSI Development Lab, along with Marty Lepselter, George E.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] As one of the few circuit designers at the lab, Abidi demonstrated the potential of sub-micron NMOS integrated circuit technology in high-speed communication circuits, and developed the first MOS amplifiers for Gb/s data rates in optical fiber receivers.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Abidi's work was initially met with skepticism from proponents of gallium arsenide and bipolar junction transistors, the dominant technologies for high-speed circuits at the time.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] In 1985, he joined UCLA, where he pioneered RF CMOS technology in the late 1980s.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] His work changed the way in which radio-frequency (RF) circuits would be designed, away from discrete bipolar transistors and towards CMOS integrated circuits.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] Abidi was researching analog CMOS circuits for signal processing and communications during the late 1980s to early 1990s.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] In the mid-1990s, the RF CMOS technology that he pioneered was widely adopted in wireless networking, as mobile phones began entering widespread use.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] As of 2008, the radio transceivers in all wireless networking devices and modern mobile phones are mass-produced as RF CMOS devices.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] The baseband processors and radio transceivers in all modern wireless networking devices and mobile phones are mass-produced using RF CMOS devices.
[src:mixed-signal-design/mixed-signal-integrated-circuit] RF CMOS technology is crucial to modern wireless communications, including wireless networks and mobile communication devices.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] A **phase-locked loop** (**PLL**) is a control system that generates an output signal whose phase is fixed relative to the phase of an input signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Keeping the input and output phase in lockstep also implies a constant relationship between input and output frequencies.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] By incorporating a frequency divider, a PLL can generate a stable frequency that is a multiple of the input frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] These properties are used for clock synchronization, demodulation, frequency synthesis, clock multipliers, and signal recovery from a noisy communication channel.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Since 1969, a single integrated circuit can provide a complete PLL building block, and nowadays has output frequencies from a fraction of a hertz up to many gigahertz.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] A simple analog PLL is an electronic circuit consisting of a variable frequency oscillator and a phase detector in a feedback loop (Figure 1).
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The oscillator generates a periodic signal *Vo* with frequency proportional to an applied voltage, hence the term voltage-controlled oscillator (VCO).
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The phase detector compares the phase of the VCO's output signal with the phase of periodic input reference signal *Vi* and outputs a voltage (stabilized by the filter) to adjust the oscillator's frequency to match the phase of *Vo* to the phase of *Vi*.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Phase can be proportional to time, so a phase difference can correspond to a time difference.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Left alone, different clocks will mark time at slightly different rates.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] A mechanical clock, for example, might be fast or slow by a few seconds per hour compared to a reference atomic clock (such as the NIST-F2).
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] That time difference becomes substantial over time.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Instead, the owner can synchronize their mechanical clock (with varying degrees of accuracy) by phase-locking it to a reference clock.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] An inefficient synchronization method involves the owner resetting their clock to that more accurate clock's time every week.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] But, left alone, their clock will still continue to diverge from the reference clock at the same few seconds per hour rate.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] A more efficient synchronization method (analogous to the simple PLL in Figure 1) utilizes the fast-slow timing adjust control (analogous to how the VCO's frequency can be adjusted) available on some clocks.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Analogously to the phase comparator, the owner could notice their clock's misalignment and turn its timing adjustment a small proportional amount to make their clock's frequency a little slower (if their clock was fast) or faster (if their clock was slow).
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] If they don't overcompensate, then their clock will be more accurate than before.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Over a series of such weekly adjustments, their clock's notion of a second would agree close enough with the reference clock, so they could be said to be locked both in frequency and phase.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] An early electromechanical version of a phase-locked loop was used in 1921 in the Shortt-Synchronome clock.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Spontaneous synchronization of weakly coupled pendulum clocks was noted by the Dutch physicist Christiaan Huygens as early as 1673.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Around the turn of the 19th century, Lord Rayleigh observed synchronization of weakly coupled organ pipes and tuning forks.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Vincent found that two electronic oscillators that had been tuned to oscillate at slightly different frequencies but that were coupled to a resonant circuit would soon oscillate at the same frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Automatic synchronization of electronic oscillators was described in 1923 by Edward Victor Appleton.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In 1923, Harry Nyquist patented a PLL with a motor-generator as the oscillator.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In 1925, David Robertson, first professor of electrical engineering at the University of Bristol, introduced phase locking in his clock design to control the striking of the bell Great George in the new Wills Memorial Building.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Robertson's clock incorporated an electromechanical device that could vary the rate of oscillation of the pendulum, and derived correction signals from a circuit that compared the pendulum phase with that of an incoming telegraph pulse from Greenwich Observatory every morning at 10:00 GMT.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Including equivalents of every element of a modern electronic PLL, Robertson's system was notably ahead of its time in that its phase detector was a relay logic implementation of the transistor circuits for phase/frequency detectors not seen until the 1970s.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Robertson's work predated research towards what was later named the phase-lock loop in 1932, when British researchers developed an alternative to Edwin Armstrong's superheterodyne receiver, the Homodyne or direct-conversion receiver.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In the homodyne or synchrodyne system, a local oscillator was tuned to the desired input frequency and multiplied with the input signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The resulting output signal included the original modulation information.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The intent was to develop an alternative receiver circuit that required fewer tuned circuits than the superheterodyne receiver.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Since the local oscillator would rapidly drift in frequency, an automatic correction signal was applied to the oscillator, maintaining it in the same phase and frequency of the desired signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The technique was described in 1932, in a paper by Henri de Bellescize, in the French journal *L'Onde Électrique*.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In analog television receivers since at least the late 1930s, phase-locked-loop horizontal and vertical sweep circuits are locked to synchronization pulses in the broadcast signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In 1969, Signetics introduced a line of low-cost monolithic integrated circuits like the NE565 using bipolar transistors, which were complete phase-locked loop systems on a chip, and applications for the technique multiplied.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] A few years later, RCA introduced the CD4046 Micropower Phase-Locked Loop using CMOS, which also became a popular integrated circuit building block.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Phase-locked loop mechanisms may be implemented as either analog or digital circuits.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Both implementations use the same basic structure.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Some terms that are used are "analog phase-locked loop" (APLL), also referred to as a linear phase-locked loop" (LPLL), "digital phase-locked loop" (DPLL), "all digital phase-locked loop" (ADPLL), and "software phase-locked loop" (SPLL).
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Phase detector, filter and oscillator are digital.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Phase detector is implemented by neuronal non-linearity, and the oscillator by rate-controlled oscillating neurons.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Functional blocks are implemented by software rather than specialized hardware.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] CP-PLL is a modification of phase-locked loops with a phase-frequency detector and square waveform signals.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Phase-locked loops are widely used for synchronization purposes; in space communications for coherent demodulation and threshold extension, bit synchronization, and symbol synchronization.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Phase-locked loops can also be used to demodulate frequency-modulated signals.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In radio transmitters, a PLL is used to synthesize new frequencies which are a multiple of a reference frequency, with the same stability as the reference frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Some data streams, especially high-speed serial data streams (such as the raw stream of data from the magnetic head of a disk drive), are sent without an accompanying clock.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The receiver generates a clock from an approximate frequency reference, and then uses a PLL to phase-align it to the data stream's signal edges.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] This process is referred to as clock recovery.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] For this scheme to work, the data stream must have edges frequently enough to correct any drift in the PLL's oscillator.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Thus, a line code with a hard upper bound on the maximum time between edges (e.g.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] 8b/10b encoding) is typically used to encode the data.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] If a clock is sent in parallel with data, that clock can be used to sample the data.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Because the clock must be received and amplified before it can drive the flip-flops, which sample the data, there will be a finite, and process-, temperature-, and voltage-dependent delay between the detected clock edge and the received data window.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] This delay limits the frequency at which data can be sent.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] One way of eliminating this delay is to include a deskew PLL on the receive side, so that the clock at each data flip-flop is phase-matched to the received clock.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In that type of application, a special form of a PLL called a delay-locked loop (DLL) is frequently used.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Many electronic systems include processors of various sorts that operate at hundreds of megahertz to gigahertz, well above the practical frequencies of crystal oscillators.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Typically, the clocks supplied to these processors come from clock generator PLLs, which multiply a lower-frequency reference clock (usually 50 or 100 MHz) up to the operating frequency of the processor.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The multiplication factor can be quite large in cases where the operating frequency is multiple gigahertz and the reference crystal is just tens or hundreds of megahertz.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] All electronic systems emit some unwanted radio frequency energy.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Various regulatory agencies (such as the FCC in the United States) put limits on the emitted energy and any interference caused by it.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The emitted noise generally appears at sharp spectral peaks (usually at the operating frequency of the device and a few harmonics).
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] A system designer can use a spread-spectrum PLL to reduce interference with high-Q receivers by spreading the energy over a larger portion of the spectrum.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Typically, the reference clock enters the chip and drives a PLL, which then drives the system's clock distribution.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The clock distribution is usually balanced so that the clock arrives at every endpoint simultaneously.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] One of those endpoints is the PLL's feedback input.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The function of the PLL is to compare the distributed clock to the incoming reference clock and vary the phase and frequency of its output until the reference and feedback clocks are phase and frequency matched.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] PLLs are ubiquitous—they tune clocks in systems several feet across, as well as clocks in small portions of individual chips.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Sometimes the reference clock may not actually be a pure clock at all, but rather a data stream with enough transitions that the PLL is able to recover a regular clock from that stream.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Sometimes the reference clock is the same frequency as the clock driven through the clock distribution, other times the distributed clock may be some rational multiple of the reference.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] A PLL may be used to synchronously demodulate amplitude-modulated (AM) signals.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The PLL recovers the phase and frequency of the incoming AM signal's carrier.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The recovered phase at the VCO differs from the carrier's by 90°, so it is shifted in phase to match and then fed to a multiplier.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The output of the multiplier contains both the sum and the difference frequency signals, and the demodulated output is obtained by low-pass filtering.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Since the PLL responds only to the carrier frequencies that are very close to the VCO output, a PLL AM detector exhibits a high degree of selectivity and noise immunity, which is not possible with conventional peak-type AM demodulators.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] However, the loop may lose lock where AM signals have 100% modulation depth.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] One desirable property of all PLLs is that the reference and feedback clock edges are brought into very close alignment.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The average difference in time between the phases of the two signals when the PLL has achieved lock is called the **static phase offset** (also called the **steady-state phase error**).
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The variance between these phases is called **tracking jitter**.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Ideally, the static phase offset should be zero, and the tracking jitter should be as low as possible.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Phase noise is another type of jitter observed in PLLs, and is caused by the oscillator itself and by elements used in the oscillator's frequency control circuit.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Some technologies are known to perform better than others in this regard.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The best digital PLLs are constructed with emitter-coupled logic (ECL) elements, at the expense of high power consumption.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] To keep phase noise low in PLL circuits, it is best to avoid saturating logic families such as transistor-transistor logic (TTL) or CMOS.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Another desirable property of all PLLs is that the phase and frequency of the generated clock are unaffected by rapid changes in the voltages of the power and ground supply lines, as well as the voltage of the substrate on which the PLL circuits are fabricated.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] This is called substrate and supply noise rejection.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The higher the noise rejection, the better.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] To further improve the phase noise of the output, an injection locked oscillator can be employed following the VCO in the PLL.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In digital wireless communication systems (GSM, CDMA, etc.), PLLs are used to provide the local oscillator up-conversion during transmission and down-conversion during reception.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In most cellular handsets, this function has been largely integrated into a single integrated circuit to reduce the cost and size of the handset.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] However, due to the high performance required of base station terminals, the transmission and reception circuits are built with discrete components to achieve the levels of performance required.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] GSM local oscillator modules are typically built with a frequency synthesizer integrated circuit and discrete resonator VCOs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Grid-tie inverters based on voltage source inverters source or sink real power into the AC electric grid as a function of the phase angle of the voltage they generate relative to the grid's voltage phase angle, which is measured using a PLL.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In photovoltaic applications, the more the sine wave produced leads the grid voltage wave, the more power is injected into the grid.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] For battery applications, the more the sine wave produced lags the grid voltage wave, the more the battery charges from the grid, and the more the sine wave produced leads the grid voltage wave, the more the battery discharges into the grid.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The block diagram shown in the figure shows an input signal, *F**I*, which is used to generate an output, *F**O*.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The input signal is often called the *reference signal* (also abbreviated *F**REF*).
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] At the input, a phase detector (shown as the Phase frequency detector and Charge pump blocks in the figure) compares two input signals, producing an error signal which is proportional to their phase difference.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The error signal is then low-pass filtered and used to drive a VCO, which creates an output phase.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The output is fed through an optional divider back to the input of the system, producing a negative feedback loop.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] If the output phase drifts, the error signal will increase, driving the VCO phase in the opposite direction so as to reduce the error.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Thus, the output phase is locked to the phase of the input.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Analog phase-locked loops are generally built with an analog phase detector, low-pass filter and VCO placed in a negative feedback configuration.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] A digital phase-locked loop uses a digital phase detector; it may also have a divider in the feedback path or in the reference path, or both, in order to make the PLL's output signal frequency a rational multiple of the reference frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] A non-integer multiple of the reference frequency can also be created by replacing the simple divide-by-*N* counter in the feedback path with a programmable pulse swallowing counter.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] This technique is usually referred to as a fractional-N synthesizer or fractional-N PLL.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The oscillator generates a periodic output signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Assume that initially the oscillator is at nearly the same frequency as the reference signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] If the phase from the oscillator falls behind that of the reference, the phase detector changes the control voltage of the oscillator so that it speeds up.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Likewise, if the phase creeps ahead of the reference, the phase detector changes the control voltage to slow down the oscillator.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Since initially the oscillator may be far from the reference frequency, practical phase detectors may also respond to frequency differences, so as to increase the lock-in range of allowable inputs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Depending on the application, either the output of the controlled oscillator or the control signal to the oscillator, provides the useful output of the PLL system.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] A phase detector (PD) generates a voltage, which represents the phase difference between two signals.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In a PLL, the two inputs of the phase detector are the reference input and the feedback from the VCO.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The PD output voltage is used to control the VCO such that the phase difference between the two inputs is held constant, making it a negative feedback system.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Different types of phase detectors have different performance characteristics.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] For instance, the frequency mixer produces harmonics that add complexity in applications where spectral purity of the VCO signal is important.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The resulting unwanted (spurious) sidebands, also called "reference spurs" can dominate the filter requirements and reduce the capture range well below or increase the lock time beyond the requirements.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In these applications, the more complex digital phase detectors are used, which do not have as severe a reference spur component on their output.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Also, when in lock, the steady-state phase difference at the inputs using this type of phase detector is near 90 degrees.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] In PLL applications, it is frequently required to know when the loop is out of lock.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The more complex digital phase-frequency detectors usually have an output that allows a reliable indication of an out-of-lock condition.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] An XOR gate is often used for digital PLLs as an effective yet simple phase detector.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] It can also be used in an analog sense, with only slight modification to the circuitry.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The block commonly called the PLL loop filter (usually a low-pass filter) generally has two distinct functions.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The primary function is to determine loop dynamics, also called stability.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] This is how the loop responds to disturbances, such as changes in the reference frequency, changes of the feedback divider, or at startup.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Common considerations are the range over which the loop can achieve lock (pull-in range, lock range or capture range), how fast the loop achieves lock (lock time, lock-up time or settling time) and damping behavior.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Depending on the application, this may require one or more of the following: a simple proportion (gain or attenuation), an integral (low-pass filter) or derivative (high-pass filter).
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Loop parameters commonly examined for this are the loop's gain margin and phase margin.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Common concepts in control theory, including the PID controller, are used to design this function.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The second common consideration is limiting the amount of reference frequency energy (ripple) appearing at the phase detector output that is then applied to the VCO control input.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] This frequency modulates the VCO and produces FM sidebands commonly called "reference spurs".
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The design of this block can be dominated by either of these considerations, or can be a complex process juggling the interactions of the two.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The typical trade-off of increasing the bandwidth is degraded stability.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Conversely, the tradeoff of extra damping for better stability is reduced speed and increased settling time.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Often, the phase noise is also affected.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] All phase-locked loops employ an oscillator element with variable frequency capability.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] This can be an analog VCO, either driven by analog circuitry in the case of an APLL or driven digitally through the use of a digital-to-analog converter as is the case for some DPLL designs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Ring oscillators are commonly used in CMOS technology for low-area applications, whereas cross-coupled LC oscillators are preferred in low-phase noise applications.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Pure digital oscillators, such as a numerically controlled oscillator, are used in ADPLLs.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] PLLs may include a divider between the oscillator and the feedback input to the phase detector to produce a frequency synthesizer.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Some PLLs also include a divider between the reference clock and the reference input to the phase detector.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] If the divider in the feedback path divides by N and the reference input divider divides by M , it allows the PLL to multiply the reference frequency by $N/M$ .
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] It might seem simpler to just feed the PLL a lower frequency, but in some cases, the reference frequency may be constrained by other issues, and then the reference divider is useful.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Frequency multiplication can also be attained by locking the VCO output to the *N*th harmonic of the reference signal.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Instead of a simple phase detector, the design uses a harmonic mixer (sampling mixer).
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The harmonic mixer turns the reference signal into an impulse train that is rich in harmonics.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The VCO output is coarse tuned to be close to one of those harmonics.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] Consequently, the desired harmonic mixer output (representing the difference between the *N* harmonic and the VCO output) falls within the loop filter passband.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] It should also be noted that the feedback is not limited to a frequency divider.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] This element can be other elements, such as a frequency multiplier or a mixer.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The multiplier will make the VCO output a sub-multiple (rather than a multiple) of the reference frequency.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] A mixer can translate the VCO frequency by a fixed offset.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] For example, a divider following a mixer allows the divider to operate at a much lower frequency than the VCO without a loss in loop gain.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The equations governing a phase-locked loop with an analog multiplier as the phase detector and linear filter may be derived as follows.
[src:mixed-signal-design/phase-locked-loop] The functions $f_{1}(\theta )$ and $f_{2}(\theta )$ describe waveforms of signals.
